Summary (as of 15/01/2021, 12:00 AM)
• Currently, the number of transmissions in the population in Germany is high. RKI now judges the level of threat to the health of the general
population as very high.
• Yesterday, 22,368 new laboratory-confirmed COVID-19 cases as well as 1,113 new deaths associated with COVID-19 were transmitted to the
RKI in Germany. The national 7-day incidence is 146 cases per 100,000 population. In Brandenburg, Saxony, Saxony-Anhalt, and Thuringia it is
markedly above the national incidence.
• All 412 districts have a high 7-day COVID-19 incidence. 312 districts have an incidence of >100 cases/100,000 population and of these,
45 districts have an incidence of >250-500 cases/100,000 population, and two districts have an incidence of >500 cases/100,000 population.
• The 7-day incidence of people 60-79 years is currently 113 and of people ≥80 years 299 cases/100,000 population.
• The high nationwide number of cases is caused by increasingly diffuse transmission, with numerous clusters especially in households,
occupational settings and nursing and long-term care homes.
• On 15/01/2021, 5,074 COVID-19 patients were in intensive care. In the preceding 24 hours, 1,607 existing patients had been discharged (16 % of
whom had died) and 1,556 patients were newly admitted. The resulting number of cases under treatment was 51 less than the prior day.
• Since 26/12/2020 a total of 961,682 people in Germany have been vaccinated against COVID-19 (11.6 vaccinated per 1,000 population)
(http://www.rki.de/covid-19-impfquoten).
• Mortality Monitoring: Mortality is significantly increased compared to the 2016-2019 average.
